      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Why O-Ending Words Matter in Scrabble</h2>
      <p>O-ending words occupy a sweet spot in Scrabble strategy. They're common enough that you'll find opportunities to play them regularly, but uncommon enough that opponents won't easily extend them with prefixes or suffixes. Unlike E-ending words (which can often be hooked with D, R, or S), O-ending words typically only accept S — and some don't even pluralise at all.</p>
      <p>The two-letter word ZO (11 points) is a hidden gem that every competitive player should know. It's a Tibetan yak hybrid, and at 11 points for two tiles, it's one of the most efficient plays in the game. Beyond short words, O-enders like GAZEBO (18 points) and ZERO (13 points) combine the letter Z with the O ending for powerful scoring. Words like DYNAMO, EMBARGO, and VOLCANO use multiple common tiles to build respectable scores through length rather than individual tile values.</p>

